If you are using DecidingScope you can have a SurtPrefixedDecideRule rule
that might look like this:

&lt;newObject name=&quot;rejectIfSurtPrefixed&quot; class=&quot;org.archive.crawler.deciderules.SurtPrefixedDecideRule&quot;&gt;
&lt;string name=&quot;decision&quot;&gt;REJECT&lt;/string&gt;
&lt;string name=&quot;surts-source-file&quot;&gt;exclude-surts.txt&lt;/string&gt;
&lt;boolean name=&quot;seeds-as-surt-prefixes&quot;&gt;false&lt;/boolean&gt;
&lt;string name=&quot;surts-dump-file&quot;&gt;&lt;/string&gt;
&lt;boolean name=&quot;also-check-via&quot;&gt;false&lt;/boolean&gt;
&lt;boolean name=&quot;rebuild-on-reconfig&quot;&gt;true&lt;/boolean&gt;
&lt;/newObject&gt;

In this case you don&#39;t need to pause the crawl at all (it is wise to do so). Just add new surt to 
exclude-surts.txt and &#39;touch&#39; (Jobs-&gt; Edit configuration-&gt;Finished) configuration.
Notice that rebuild-on-reconfig is set to true. This will re-read the surt file and update the 
crawler. Be aware, that if the list of excluded hosts is very large (tens of thousands) it will take 
a while to re-configure the rule.

Other option is to use per host overrides and preselector block-all.

Hope this helps.
i.

